{"key":"processedPost-17889399","value":{"id":17889399,"first":17887850,"last":17889461,"when":1362200835,"utime":"03/02/13 07:07 AM","cleanedPost":"Peat doesn't work at all as a substrate.&nbsp; Coir is found in cities at pet stores.&nbsp; Get it the blocks.&nbsp; Avoid the coir from hydro stores as it usually has bacillus and trichoderma added since they're beneficial to plants.<br />Composted cow manure from a nursery or plant store works too, but mix it 50/50 with vermiculite to fluff it up and add minerals.<br />If neighbors have horses, horse manure is the gold standard.&nbsp; Collect field aged nuggets that have been out in the sun for at least a month or two.&nbsp; As long as they're dry and the ammonia smell is gone, they're ready to pasteurize and use.<br />RR"}}